            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text of Alföldy (1983) compared with photograph</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>[---] lay the foundations of [the temple to Eternal Roma and] the Augusti, [with porticos and ornaments]. His son, [?] Caecilius Secundus dedicated it.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Alföldy (1983) was the first to associate this inscription with <ref target="EmpWor000833.xml">EmpWor000833</ref>, and thus reconstruct with certainty the lacunae around the dedicatory formula for the temple attested in both: the Temple of Aeternitas Roma and the Augusti. Financed by L. Caecilius Secundus in the name of his daughter, Caecilia. The "filius" ("son") who undertook the dedication of the structure is likely Pliny the Younger, before he was adopted by his maternal uncle (Pliny the Elder) in 79 CE.</p> 
            </div>
